The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Sunday, July 18, 2004 				 Dowry law in Kerala
																								Thiruvananthapuram, July 17 (PTI): The Kerala government has made it compulsory for male employees to file a declaration stating they had not received dowry in a move to discourage the practice among the salaried class.																								An amendment to the Dowry Prohibition Act 1961 has also made it mandatory for the declaration  to be submitted by an employee to the head of the department  to carry the signatures of the employees father, father-in-law and wife, an official media release said.																								The changes, drawn up on the basis of the state womens commission recommendations, provide for appointment of dowry prohibition officers in three regions in the state, to register complaints regarding violation of dowry rules. They can initiate prosecution procedures against the offender if a preliminary probe establishes a prima facie case.																								The regional dowry prohibition officers will also have to send quarterly reports to the chief dowry prohibition officer about complaints received and action taken. The director of social welfare department has been designated chief dowry officer. 
